  "prompt": "When people say \"Maths\" instead of \"Math\" are they indicating plurality in some way?",
  "response": "The term \"maths,\" which is commonly used in British English, is not an indication of plurality. Instead, it is an abbreviation of the word \"mathematics.\" The word \"mathematics\" itself is derived from the Greek \"mathematika,\" which means things that are learned. Despite the plural form in Greek, mathematics is treated as a singular noun when referring to the field of study.\n\nIn American English, the abbreviation \"math\" is preferred, while in British English, \"maths\" is more commonly used. Both abbreviations refer to the same subject, and the difference is simply a matter of regional language preference, not plurality.",
